Now I need to understand the issue better. Looking at the test method `testPropertyOptionFlags`, I can see that the problem is with how the `processProperties` method handles flags (options without arguments). Let me analyze the bug:

The test expects that when a property has a value "false", "no", or anything that's not "yes", "true", or "1", then the option should NOT be added to the CommandLine if it's a flag-type option (no arguments). However, there seems to be an issue in line 236-246 of the `processProperties` method.

Looking at the problematic section in the `processProperties` method:

```java
else if (!("yes".equalsIgnoreCase(value)
        || "true".equalsIgnoreCase(value)
        || "1".equalsIgnoreCase(value)))
{
    // if the value is not yes, true or 1 then don't add the
    // option to the CommandLine
    break;
}
```

This code has a bug. The `break` statement exits the entire loop (the `for` loop that iterates over property names), rather than just skipping the current property. This means if any property has a value that's not "yes", "true", or "1", then all subsequent properties won't be processed.

